All Classes

  • All Classes Interface Summary Class Summary Enum Summary Exception Summary 
    Class Description
    Area
    An Area is a single room or outdoor scene in which the player can exist, containing its own TiledMap texture and set of Interactable objects.
    Area.Name
    Distinguishes between the standard Area instantiations
    AreaFactory
    The AreaFactory provides a non-static factory for initialising particular Area objects, populated with Interactable objects
    AreaMetric
    An AreaMetric represents an Area as a MetricEntry to be managed by the MetricController
    Character
    The Character class represents the avatar of the player in the game, extending the Sprite.
    DesktopLauncher
    Provides the JVM system entry point to launch the desktop Lwjgl3Application with the HeslingtonHustle instance, specifying certain fixed application configuration parameters.
    DOWMetric
    A DOWMetric represents a singular day of the week to be managed by the MetricController
    DOWMetric.DayOfWeek
    Distinguish between days of the week with the default Enum.toString() methods for display
    Drawable
    A Drawable represents a Disposable that may be rendered to a SpriteBatch
    GameMap
    A GameMap represents and manages the Drawable playing Area background, principally consisting of the TiledMap.
    GameOverMenu
    The GameOverMenu should display once the final day has been reached
    HeadsUpDisplay
    The HeadsUpDisplay displays persistent player and game information throughout the gameplay.
    HeslingtonHustle
    The Game is the ApplicationListener shared by all platforms.
    Interactable
    An Interactable is an Item with which the Character may interact.
    InvalidAreaException
    An InvalidAreaException indicates that an Area could not properly be loaded
    Item
    An Item denotes a drawable non-Character object.
    MetricController
    A MetricController stores and manages many MetricEntry items and their associated MetricController.Metric keys, providing a unified interface through which higher-level controllers may manipulate the values of MetricEntry objects and post runtime alteration updates to the MetricUpdater.
    MetricController.Metric
    Distinguish between the standard metrics represented in the MetricEntry objects
    MetricEntry
    A MetricEntry implementation denotes a metric of a particular type, e.g.
    MetricListener
    A MetricListener is interested in receives updates from a MetricController through the corresponding MetricUpdater.
    MetricUpdater
    The MetricUpdater provides a common controller to link a single MetricController and MetricListener, by means of enabling the former to post updates to the latter
    Overlay
    An Overlay denotes a distinctly Drawable scene, typically rendered on top of a Screen
    OverlayFactory
    The OverlayFactory constructs types of Overlay objects given with a persistent SpriteBatch
    PauseMenu
    The PauseMenu provides a pleasant Overlay to display upon a pause being requested, or a game Screen losing focus.
    PlayerMetric
    A PlayerMetric represents a MetricEntry pertaining to the player-controlled character to be managed by the MetricController.
    PlayScreen
    The PlayScreen class represents a screen which is shown after the game starts, implementing Screen interface.
    PlayScreen.GameState
    Distinguish between internal game states; used to inform, among others, the PlayScreen.render(float)} and PlayScreen.handleInput() cycles
    StartupHelper
    Adds some utilities to ensure that the JVM was started with the -XstartOnFirstThread argument, which is required on macOS for LWJGL 3 to function.
